abstract: A QUIET SUNDAY.--The City yesterday was perfectly quiet, and our stay-at-home citizens enjoyed the unusual luxury of a day of rest from all sorts of mobs and riotous gatherings. abstract: FIRES IN BROOKLYN.--The vat-house of the American Oil Company, Red Hook Point, accidentally caught fire at 3 o'clock yesterday morning. Before the firemen could reach the spot the flames communicated with a quantity of oil in casks, stored in a yard adjoining the premises where the fire originated, and the whole was consumed. Loss $6,000--no insurance.

abstract: THE MORMONS.--The Peoria (III.) Transcript notices the arrival, at that place, of about four hundred Mormons, on their way to Salt Lake City. Most of them are English, and on being conversed with expressed dissatisfaction at the prospect thus far, and intimated a determination not to proceed to Utah. The Liverpool Albion informs us that a few weeks since, about nine Mormon elders visited Rockdale, fcr the purpose of holding services in the open air.

abstract: The most remarkable feature of America is the Basin of the Mississippi. As yet the popular mind does not clearly comprehend its dimensions, and the understanding of its physical characteristics is indistinct and vague. It is bisected through its centre by a supreme artery, which above St. Louis has received the name of the Missouri, and below, the Mississippi River.

abstract: Five Brave Men Attack one Unprotected FEMALE,-On Tuesday night, NARGARET WHERTY, a servant girl, was passing through Twenty-sixth-street, when five young men attacked her, when near Fourth-avenue, and demanded her money. She answered that she had none, and two of the gang then seized her by the arms and held her while another stole a gold breastpin from her shawl. The girl screamed for help and the scoundrels fled.
